'''Takekunihiko no Mikoto''' (武国彦命, birth and death dates unknown) was a [[Kofun period]] noble. He is also known as '''Takedainin no Mikoto''' (建大臣命) or '''Takeōomi no Mikoto''' (武大臣命).

== Overview ==
Takekunihiko no Mikoto is referred to by alternate names such as '''Takeōomi no Mikoto'''<ref>{{ill|Nakata Norinobu|ja|中田憲信|12=draft|12=draft}}. "諏訪氏", in 『諸系譜』, Vol. 13.</ref> and '''Takedainin no Mikoto'''<ref>{{ill|Enkawa Kazuhiko|ja|延川和彦|12=draft|12=draft}}, "諏訪氏系図," in 『修補諏訪氏系図.正編』,飯田好太郎, 1921, p. 25.</ref>.

According to the traditions of the Suwa Shrine's Middle Shrine in {{ill|Hokuto, Yamanashi|ja|北杜市|12=draft|12=draft}}, and the accounts in 『甲斐国史』, during the reign of {{ill|Emperor Sujin|ja|崇神天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Takenumakawabete no Mikoto|ja|建沼河別命|12=draft|12=draft}} was granted lands in the western region for his contributions during the eastern expedition. His grandson, Dainin no Mikoto, was reportedly appointed as the {{ill|Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|国造|12=draft|12=draft}} of Suwa Province and established a shrine there.

In a manuscript of the {{ill|Kuni no Miyatsuko Honki|ja|国造本紀|12=draft|12=draft}}, there is mention of his appointment as Suwa no Kuni no Miyatsuko during the reign of {{ill|Emperor Keikō|ja|景行天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}, although some theories suggest this might be a mistaken reference to {{ill|Nasu no Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|那須国造|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>Yuichi Sato, 『シナノの国造勢力』.</ref>

