== Overview == Takekunihiko no Mikoto is referred to by alternate names such as '''Takeōomi no Mikoto'''<ref>{{ill|Nakata Norinobu|ja|中田憲信|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakata Norinobu|qq=}}. "諏訪氏", in 『諸系譜』, Vol. 13.</ref> and '''Takedainin no Mikoto'''<ref>{{ill|Enkawa Kazuhiko|ja|延川和彦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enkawa Kazuhiko|qq=}}, "諏訪氏系図," in 『修補諏訪氏系図.正編』,飯田好太郎, 1921, p. 25.</ref>.
According to the traditions of the Suwa Shrine's Middle Shrine in [[:en:Hokuto, Yamanashi|Hokuto, Yamanashi]], and the accounts in 『甲斐国史』, during the reign of [[:en:Emperor Sujin|Emperor Sujin]], {{ill|Take Nunokawa Wake no Mikoto|lt=Take Nunokawa Wake no Mikoto|lt=Takenumakawabete no Mikoto|ja|建沼河別命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takenumakawabete no Mikoto|qq=}} was granted lands in the western region for his contributions during the eastern expedition. His grandson, Dainin no Mikoto, was reportedly appointed as the [[:en:Kuni no miyatsuko|Kuni no Miyatsuko]] of Suwa Province and established a shrine there.
In a manuscript of the {{ill|Kuni no Miyatsuko Honki|ja|国造本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuni no Miyatsuko Honki|qq=}}, there is mention of his appointment as Suwa no Kuni no Miyatsuko during the reign of [[:en:Emperor Keikō|Emperor Keikō]], although some theories suggest this might be a mistaken reference to {{ill|Nasu no Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|那須国造|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nasu no Kuni no Miyatsuko|qq=}}.<ref>Yuichi Sato, 『シナノの国造勢力』.</ref>
